# 🚀 Git Ignore Hands-On Lab

## 📖 Overview

This lab demonstrates how to use the `.gitignore` file in Git to exclude unwanted files and folders from version control. Ignoring unnecessary files helps keep repositories clean and prevents temporary or generated files from being committed.

---

## 🎯 Objectives

- Understand the purpose of `.gitignore`
- Learn how to ignore unwanted files
- Learn how to ignore folders from Git tracking
- Verify ignored files using Git status

---

## 🛠️ Prerequisites

- Git installed and configured
- Notepad++ configured as the default editor
- Local Git repository available
- GitHub/GitLab repository (optional)

---

## 📂 Files and Folders Created

### Log File

```text
app.log
```

### Log Folder

```text
logs/
└── error.log
```

---

## ⚙️ .gitignore Configuration

Create a `.gitignore` file and add:

```text
*.log
logs/
```

### Explanation

| Rule | Purpose |
|--------|---------|
| `*.log` | Ignores all log files |
| `logs/` | Ignores the entire logs folder |

---

## 💻 Commands Used

### Create Log File

```bash
echo Sample Log > app.log
```

### Create Log Folder

```bash
mkdir logs
echo Error Log > logs/error.log
```

### Create .gitignore

```bash
notepad .gitignore
```

### Check Status

```bash
git status
```

### Add and Commit

```bash
git add .gitignore
git commit -m "Added gitignore configuration"
```

---

## ✅ Verification

After configuring `.gitignore`, the following files should not appear in Git status:

```text
app.log
logs/error.log
logs/
```

Only `.gitignore` should be tracked.

Example:

```text
On branch master
nothing to commit, working tree clean
```

---

## 📁 Repository Structure

```text
GitDemo
│
├── .gitignore
├── README.md
├── welcome.txt
├── app.log      (ignored)
└── logs/        (ignored)
    └── error.log
```

---

## 🎓 Learning Outcomes

After completing this lab, I was able to:

- Configure a `.gitignore` file
- Ignore specific file types
- Ignore directories
- Verify ignored files using Git status
- Maintain a clean Git repository

---

## ✅ Conclusion

The `.gitignore` file is an important Git feature that prevents unnecessary files and folders from being tracked. This helps maintain an organized repository and improves version control management.